{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564921","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564921"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:20:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:20:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17167"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17167"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.39,0.03,0.12,0.42]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9857"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102956"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9857"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17167"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85422"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1638"},{"type":"tags","id":"2105"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3817"},{"type":"tags","id":"3818"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23107"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36279"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43689"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44694"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44807"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102956"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a one month history of progressive abdominal swelling and pelvic discomfort. This was associated with three months of early satiety. She reports unintentional weight loss of 8 kg over this period. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She works as an accountant and has never smoked.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her abdomen is distended with shifting dullness. Bimanual examination reveals bilateral, firm, irregular adnexal masses. A CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis shows bilateral ovarian masses, ascites, and diffuse gastric wall thickening.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely primary site of malignancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Breast","Stomach","Pancreas","Colon","Ovary"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of Krukenberg tumours - bilateral ovarian metastases typically characterised by mucin-producing signet ring cells. The presence of bilateral ovarian masses, along with gastric wall thickening on imaging, strongly suggests metastatic disease from a gastric primary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStomach\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common primary site for Krukenberg tumours, accounting for approximately 70% of cases. The presence of early satiety and weight loss further supports a gastric primary. Gastric adenocarcinoma has a particular propensity to metastasise to the ovaries via both lymphatic and transcoelomic routes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColon\u003C/strong\u003E cancer can metastasise to the ovaries, but this occurs less frequently than gastric cancer. When colorectal cancer spreads to the ovaries, it typically presents with concurrent bowel symptoms, which are absent in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBreast\u003C/strong\u003E cancer can metastasise to the ovaries but rarely presents with bilateral ovarian masses as the initial manifestation. Breast metastases to the ovaries typically occur in the setting of known breast cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPancreatic\u003C/strong\u003E cancer rarely metastasises to the ovaries. When it does, patients typically present with more prominent upper abdominal symptoms and jaundice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOvary\u003C/strong\u003E as a primary site would be unlikely given the bilateral nature of the masses and the gastric wall thickening. Primary ovarian cancer typically presents as a unilateral mass, although bilateral involvement can occur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of Krukenberg tumours generally indicates a poor prognosis as they represent metastatic disease. Management typically involves systemic chemotherapy, although surgical debulking may be considered in selected cases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Krukenberg tumours are metastatic ovarian tumours most commonly originating from gastric cancer.","Bilateral ovarian involvement is characteristic of Krukenberg tumours.","The presence of Krukenberg tumours indicates poor prognosis as they represent metastatic disease."],"references":["Zulfiqar M, Koen J, Nougaret S, Bolan C, VanBuren W, McGettigan M, et al. Krukenberg Tumors: Update on Imaging and Clinical Features. American Journal of Roentgenology. 2020 Oct;215(4):1020\u20139."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85422"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17167"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85422"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-17T17:10:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-17T17:11:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9857"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102956"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type